    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Refers to the Pre-Columbian culture and style that flourished in the Guayas River basin of coastal Ecuador ca. 700-1500 CE. Noted for large chiefdoms in a lowland landscape, the use of sophisticated cultivation of the seasonally flooded river wetlands, and the construction of large elevated earthen platforms called "tolas," which were used for both habitation and burial.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000049830/Oxford Companion to Western Art [online] (2008-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>指西元700年至1500年之間、興盛於厄瓜多爾沿海岸地區瓜亞斯河（Guayas／瓜亞河／瓜加河）流域之前哥倫布時代文化與風格。其特徵為位於低地地區的大型酋邦，並在定期氾濫的河川溼地進行高度發展的農耕活動，並建造名為「多拉斯（tolas)」的大型土堆高台作為居住和埋葬用途。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
      </Descriptive_Note>
    </Descriptive_Notes>
